3  Gold Coast 21.13 (139) v Hawthorn 7.11 (53), [[2017 AFL season#Round 3|Round 3, 2017]], [[Metricon Stadium]]\n*'''Greatest losing margin:''' 722 points \u2013 Gold Coast 0.1 (1) v Geelong 100.123 (723), [[2011 AFL season#Round 20|Round 20, 2011]], [[Kardinia Park (stadium)|Kardinia Park]]\n*'''Longest winning streak:''' 5 (round 5, 2014 &ndash; round 10, 2014)\n*'''Longest losing streak:''' 21 (round 18, 2011 &ndash; round 15, 2012)\n*'''Highest ladder position:''' 12th, [[2014 AFL season]]\n*'''Lowest ladder position:''' 18th (Wooden Spoon), [[2019 AFL season]]\n\n===AFL finishing positions (2011\u2013present)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#bdb76b;\"\n! Finishing Position !! Year ([[AFL finals series|Finals]] in Bold)!!Tally\n|-\n|'''Premiers'''||nil||'''0'''\n|-\n|'''Runner Up'''||nil||'''0'''\n|-\n|3rd||nil||'''0'''\n|-\n|4th||nil||'''0'''\n|-\n|5th||nil||'''0'''\n|-\n|6th||nil||'''0'''\n|-\n|7th||nil||'''0'''\n|-\n|8th||nil||'''0'''\n|-\n|9th||nil||'''0'''\n|-\n|10th||nil||'''0'''\n|-\n|11th||nil||'''0'''\n|-\n|12th||2014||'''1'''\n|-\n|13th||nil||'''0'''\n|-\n|14th||2013||'''1'''\n|-\n|15th||2016||'''1'''\n|-\n|16th||2015||'''1'''\n|-\n|17th||2011, 2012, 2017, 2018||'''4'''\n|-\n|18th||2019||'''1'''\n|}\n\n==Individual awards==\n\n<div style=\"float:left; width:48%;\">\n'''[[All-Australian team]]'''\n*[[Gary Ablett, Jr.|Gary Ablett Jr]]: [[All-Australian team#2011|2011]] (c), [[All-Australian team#2012|2012]] (vc), [[All-Australian team#2013|2013]] (vc), [[All-Australian team#2014|2014]]\n*[[Tom Lynch (Australian footballer, born 1992)|Tom Lynch]]: [[2016 All-Australian team|2016]]\n\n'''[[Leigh Matthews Trophy]]'''\n*[[Gary Ablett, Jr.|Gary Ablett Jr]]: [[Leigh Matthews Trophy#Winners|2012]], [[Leigh Matthews Trophy#Winners|2013]]\n\n</div>\n\n<div style=\"float:right; width:48%;\">\n\n'''[[Brownlow Medal]]'''\n*[[Gary Ablett, Jr.|Gary Ablett Jr]]: [[2013 Brownlow Medal|2013]]\n\n'''[[AFL Rising Star|Ron Evans Medal]]'''\n*[[Jaeger O'Meara]]: [[AFL Rising Star#Winners|2013]]\n</div>{{Clear}}\n\n==Suns TV==\nSuns TV was a television program hosted by [[Jessica Skarratt]] that was carried by the [[Seven Network]] and was shown thirty minutes prior to Gold Coast Suns games in Queensland. The program featured highlights as well as interviews with players and coaches in the lead up to the match being played that week. It was no longer shown on TV as of 2015.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Queensland|Sports|Australia}}\n*[[Sport in Australia]]\n*[[Sport in Queensland]]\n*[[Australian Rules Football]]\n*[[Australian rules football in Queensland]]\n*[[History of Australian rules football on the Gold Coast]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.goldcoastfc.com.au/ Gold Coast Suns website]\n* [http://www.southportsharks.com.au/ Southport Sharks website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100713012630/http://www.goldcoastfc.com.au/events/results-2010-vfl/ 2010 VFL results page] at [http://goldcoastfc.com.au goldcoastfc.com.au]\n\n{{Gold Coast Suns}}\n{{Australian Football League}}\n{{AFL Women's}}\n{{NEAFL}}\n{{VFL}}\n{{Aussie Rules in Queensland}}\n{{Gold Coast Sports Teams}}\n\n[[Category:Gold Coast Suns| ]]\n[[Category:Australian Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:Sport on the Gold Coast, Queensland]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 2009]]\n[[Category:2009 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian rules football clubs in Queensland]]\n[[Category:Former NAB League clubs]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Australian rules football team|the rugby league team|Gold Coast Titans|the baseball team|Gold Coast Suns (baseball)|the soccer team|Gold Coast United FC}}\n{{short description|Australian rules football club}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox australian football club\n|color1 = #FF0000\n|color2 = #FFE600\n|color3 = solid #006FBA\n| clubname  = Gold Coast Suns\n| image     = [[File:Gold Coast Suns logo.svg|200px]]\n| fullname  = Gold Coast Suns Football Club\n| nicknames = Suns\n| season    = [[2019 AFL season|<span style=\"color:#FFE600\">2019</span>]]\n| pre-season = \n| home&away  = 18th\n| topgoalkicker =  [[Alex Sexton]] (39 goals)\n| bestandfairest = [[Jarrod Witts]]\n| bestandfairestname = Gold Coast Suns Club Champion\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2009}}\n| colours = {{color box|#FF0000}} Red<br />{{color box|#FFE600}} Gold<br />{{colour box|#006FBA}} Blue\n| league    = '''[[Australian Football League|AFL]]:''' Senior men<br>'''[[AFL Women's|AFLW]]:''' Senior women<br>'''[[North East Australian Football League|NEAFL]]:''' Reserves men\n| chairman  = [[Tony Cochrane]]\n| coach     = '''AFL:''' [[Stuart Dew]]<br>'''AFLW:''' [[David Lake (coach)|David Lake]]<br>'''NEAFL:''' [[Nick Malceski]]\n| captain   = '''AFL:''' [[David Swallow]] & [[Jarrod Witts]]<br>'''AFLW:''' [[Leah Kaslar]] & [[Sam Virgo]]<br>'''NEAFL:''' TBC  \n| premierships = Nil\n| ground    = [[Carrara Stadium|Metricon Stadium]]\n| capacity  = 25,000\n| formerground = \n| span      = \n| trainingground = [[Metricon Stadium]] & [[Gold Coast Sports and Leisure Centre]]\n| kit_alt1        = \n| pattern_b1      = _goldcoastsuns\n| pattern_sh1     = \n| pattern_so1     = _yellowtop\n| body1           = FF0000\n| shorts1         = FF0000\n| socks1          = FF0000\n| pattern_b2     = _goldcoastsuns\n| pattern_sh2     = \n| pattern_so2     = _yellowtop\n| body2          = 006FBA\n| shorts2         = \n| socks2          = 006FBA\n| url       = [http://goldcoastfc.com.au/ goldcoastfc.com.au]\n| jumper    = \n| current   = \n}}\n\nThe '''Gold Coast Suns Football Club''' is a professional [[Australian rules football]] club in the [[Australian Football League]] (AFL). The club is based on the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]], [[Queensland]].\n\nThe club has been playing in the AFL since the [[2011 AFL season|2011 season]], having been founded as the league's 17th active club by a consortium formerly known as \"GC17\" and being granted a licence to join the AFL on 1 April 2009.<ref name=\"ABC_Sports_31Mar209_GoldCoastFC_Licence\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/03/31/2530986.htm|title=Gold Coast gets AFL licence|date=1 April 2009|work=ABC News}}</ref> The team is based in the Gold Coast suburb of [[Carrara, Queensland|Carrara]] and play matches at [[Carrara Stadium]] (known for commercial purposes as \"Metricon Stadium\") and train at the adjacent [[Gold Coast Sports and Leisure Centre]]. The club is one of two AFL clubs based in Queensland, the other being its main rival, the [[Brisbane Lions]]. The Suns also field teams in the [[AFL Women's]] and [[North East Australian Football League]]s.\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of the Gold Coast Suns}}\n\nIn January 2008, it was reported that the AFL officially registered the name \"Gold Coast Football Club Ltd\" with the [[Australian Securities and Investments Commission]] (ASIC).<ref name=Silence/> The registration was effective from 24 December 2007.<ref name=ASIC_Registration_GCFC>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.search.asic.gov.au/cgi-bin/gns030c?acn=129_026_857|title = ASIC Free Company Name Search|accessdate=7 September 2008|publisher=[[Australian Securities and Investments Commission|ASIC]]}}</ref> In March 2008, the AFL won the support of the league's 16 club presidents to establish a side on the Gold Coast and an 18th side in Western Sydney.\n\n===Establishment===\nAFL CEO [[Andrew Demetriou]] announced in early 2008 that the club could debut in the [[Queensland State League (Australian rules football)|Queensland State League]] in 2009 as it recruited players and prepared for its debut season in the AFL.<ref>{{cite news | url =http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/news/gold-coast-to-play-in-2009/2008/03/22/1205602735993.html | title =Gold Coast to play in 2009| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080326181541/http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/news/gold-coast-to-play-in-2009/2008/03/22/1205602735993.html|archivedate=26 March 2008}}</ref> Amongst the first players targeted by the Gold Coast were former {{AFL Stk}} captain and Gold Coast junior [[Nick Riewoldt]],<ref>[http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/afl/afl-news/gold-coast-to-target-riewoldt-20091124-j8e5.html Gold Coast to target Riewoldt]</ref> {{AFL Haw}} forward and 2008 [[Coleman Medal]]list [[Lance Franklin]]<ref>[http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/buddy-plays-it-cool/story-0-1225700592624 Buddy Franklin plays it cool on Gold Coast talk | thetelegraph.com.au]</ref> and {{AFL Ade}} forward [[Kurt Tippett]].<ref>[http://www.goldcoast.com.au/article/2008/05/20/11318_afl-sport.html Tippett should be tip-top Coast AFL target AFL | goldcoast.com.au | Gold Coast, Queensland, Australia]</ref> They did not end up with any of them.\n\nIn June 2008 it was announced that the new team would play in the [[TAC Cup]] in 2009<ref>[http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/news/tac-cup-to-help-blood-new-team/2008/06/04/1212258909342.html TAC Cup to help blood new team]; realfooty.com.au</ref> and then in the [[VFL]] in 2010.\n\n[[Guy McKenna]] was appointed coach in August 2008.<ref>[http://news.smh.com.au/sport/guy-mckenna-named-gold-coast-afl-coach-20080813-3ujb.html Guy McKenna named Gold Coast AFL coach] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080813041718/http://news.smh.com.au/sport/guy-mckenna-named-gold-coast-afl-coach-20080813-3ujb.html |date=13 August 2008 }}</ref> In early 2009, the Host Plus superannuation fund was named as the club's major sponsor.\n<ref>\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.goldcoastfc.com.au/the-club/sponsors-and-partners/ \n |title=Gold Coast FC.com.au \n |date=29 July 2009 \n |accessdate=29 July 2009 \n |publisher=Gold Coast Football Club \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091015010905/http://www.goldcoastfc.com.au/the-club/sponsors-and-partners/ \n |archivedate=15 October 2009 \n |df=dmy \n}}\n</ref> On 15 May 2009, it was announced that [[Essendon Football Club]] administrator Travis Auld would be the CEO of \"GC17\".<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_News_2009May15_GCFC17\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/05/15/2571530.htm|title=Bombers boss named Gold Coast CEO|date=15 May 2009|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=19 May 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_News_2009May18_GCFC17\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/05/18/2573641.htm|title='Big challenges' face new Gold Coast FC boss|date=18 May 2009|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=19 May 2009}}</ref> Former Brisbane Lions' [[Shaun Hart]] and Gold Coaster [[Marcus Ashcroft]] were also appointed to the coaching panel. On 1 October 2009, the club announced it had signed Guy McKenna as head coach until 2012.<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_News_2009Oct01_Sport_McKennaGFCHeadCoachuntil2012\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/10/01/2701925.htm|title=Gold Coast names coach, denies Fev|date=1 October 2009|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=1 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2009, the Queensland government announced that it would contribute sufficient funds allowing the redevelopment of Gold Coast Stadium. The redevelopment of [[Carrara Stadium]] cost $144.2 million to complete and housed 25,000 spectators with the capability to host an additional 15,000 temporary seats.<ref>http://www.goldcoastbulletin.com.au</ref> The club's first game at the new stadium was against [[Geelong Football Club|Geelong]] in round 10, 2011 after hosting their first few home matches at the Gabba.\n\n===2009: TAC Cup===\nThe club's junior squad competed in the 2009 [[TAC Cup]] under 18 competition winning a number of games, eventually finishing in 5th place.  They defeated the [[Northern Knights]] in the elimination final but then lost their semi final to the [[Geelong Falcons]]. Below is the inaugural TAC Cup team to play for the Gold Coast Football Club, as well as a table of results and fixture for the 2009 and 2010 seasons:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldcoastfc.com.au/events/results/ |title=Gold Coast Football Club \u2013 AFL \u2013 Results |publisher=Gold Coast FC.com.au |accessdate=11 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091015052505/http://www.goldcoastfc.com.au/events/results/ |archivedate=15 October 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldcoastfc.com.au/events/tac-cup-fixture/ |title=Gold Coast Football Club \u2013 AFL \u2013 TAC Cup Fixture |publisher=Gold Coast FC.com.au |accessdate=11 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091016092754/http://www.goldcoastfc.com.au/events/tac-cup-fixture/ |archivedate=16 October 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===={{anchor|Inaugural TAC Cup team}}Inaugural TAC Cup team====\n{{Aussie rules team | title = Inaugural GC17 team (Round 1, 2009 season)\n| backpocket1 = Hamish Watts\n| fullback = James Nelis\n| backpocket2 = Daniel Ramage\n| halfbackflank1 = Jake Crawford\n| centrehalfback = Matt Storey\n| halfbackflank2 = Jesse Haberfield\n| wing1 = [[Joseph Daye]]\n| centre = [[Josh Thomas (Australian footballer)|Josh Thomas]]\n| wing2 = Todd Grayson\n| halfforwardflank1 = Taylor Rolfe\n| centrehalfforward = Matt Fowler\n| halfforwardflank2 = Luke Shreeve\n| forwardpocket1 = [[Rory Thompson]]\n| fullforward = Liam Rutledge\n| forwardpocket2 = [[Alik Magin]]\n| ruck = [[Zac Smith]]\n| ruckrover = [[Marc Lock]] ([[Captain (Australian rules football)|c]])\n| rover = Mitch Harley\n| interchange1 = Declan Bevan\n| interchange2 = Brad Rees\n| interchange3 = Jack Stanlake\n| interchange4 = Nick Price\n| interchange5 = Tyler Green\n| coach = [[Guy McKenna]]<ref name=\"tac cup team\">{{cite news\n|url=http://www.goldcoast.com.au/article/2009/04/04/66181_gold-coast-sport.html\n|title=Teen talent galore at historic debut\n|date=4 April 2009\n|work=Gold Coast Bulletin\n|accessdate=5 April 2009}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed wikitable toccolours\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:white; color:black; width:670px;\"|'''Gold Coast Season 2009'''\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| '''Rd'''\n| '''Home team'''\n| '''Score'''\n|\n| '''Away team'''\n| '''Score'''\n| '''Ground'''\n| '''Date'''\n|-\n| 1\n| Gold Coast\n| 9.10 (64)\n| def by\n| '''[[Eastern Ranges]]'''\n| '''16.6 (102)'''\n| [[Carrara Stadium]]\n| Saturday, 4 April\n|-\n| 2\n| [[Western Jets]]\n| 5.5 (35)\n| def by\n| '''Gold Coast'''\n| '''26.13 (169)'''\n| [[Burbank Oval]]\n| Sunday, 12 April\n|-\n| 3\n| ''Bye''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| 4\n| '''[[Tassie Mariners]]'''\n| '''4.5 (29)'''\n| drew with\n| '''Gold Coast'''\n| '''3.11 (29)'''\n| [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n| Sunday, 26 April\n|-\n| 5\n| '''[[Calder Cannons]]'''\n| '''18.11 (119)'''\n| def\n| Gold Coast\n| 15.13 (103)\n| [[Coburg City Oval|ABD Group Stadium]]\n| Sunday, 3 May\n|-\n| 6\n| '''Gold Coast'''\n| '''12.7 (79)'''\n| def\n| [[Gippsland Power]]\n| 12.5 (77)\n| [[Carrara Stadium]]\n| Saturday, 9 May\n|-\n| 7\n| '''Gold Coast'''\n| '''9.11 (65)'''\n| def\n| [[Dandenong Stingrays]]\n| 8.12 (60)\n| [[Carrara Stadium]]\n| Saturday, 16 May\n|-\n| 8\n| Gold Coast\n| 10.9 (69)\n| def by\n| '''[[NSW/ACT Rams]]'''\n| '''14.10 (94)'''\n| [[Carrara Stadium]]\n| Saturday, 23 May\n|-\n| 9\n| '''Gold Coast'''\n| '''7.13 (55)'''\n| def\n| [[Oakleigh Chargers]]\n| 7.10 (52)\n| [[Carrara Stadium]]\n| Saturday, 30 May\n|-\n| 10\n| '''Gold Coast'''\n| '''10.17 (77)'''\n| def\n| [[North Ballarat Rebels]]\n| 11.4 (70)\n| [[Carrara Stadium]]\n| Saturday, 13 June\n|-\n| 11\n| '''[[Tassie Mariners]]'''\n| '''16.14 (110)'''\n| def\n| Gold Coast\n| 7.6 (48)\n| [[York Park|Aurora Stadium]]\n| Saturday, 20 June\n|-\n| 12\n| ''Bye''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| 13\n| Gold Coast\n| 5.8 (38)\n| def by\n| '''[[Murray Bushrangers]]'''\n| '''14.9 (93)'''\n| [[Carrara Stadium]]\n| Saturday, 4 July\n|-\n| 14\n| '''Gold Coast'''\n| '''13.16 (94)'''\n| def\n| [[Northern Knights]]\n| 10.6 (66)\n| [[Carrara Stadium]]\n| Saturday, 11 July\n|-\n| 15\n| '''Gold Coast'''\n| '''13.16 (94)'''\n| def\n| [[Western Jets]]\n| 10.6 (66)\n| [[Carrara Stadium]]\n| Saturday, 18 July\n|-\n| 16\n| '''[[North Ballarat Rebels]]'''\n| '''8.14 (62)'''\n| def\n| Gold Coast\n| 7.6 (48)\n| [[Northern Oval]]\n| Saturday, 26 July\n|-\n| 17\n| '''Gold Coast'''\n| '''15.16 (106)'''\n| def\n| [[Sandringham Dragons]]\n| 8.2 (50)\n| [[Carrara Stadium]]\n| Sunday, 2 August\n|-\n| 18\n| '''Gold Coast'''\n| '''12.14 (86)'''\n| def\n| [[Bendigo Pioneers]]\n| 6.11 (47)\n| [[Carrara Stadium]]\n| Saturday, 15 August\n|-\n| 19\n| [[Gippsland Power]]\n| 10.9 (69)\n| def by\n| '''Gold Coast'''\n| '''12.14 (86)'''\n| [[Princes Park (stadium)|Visy Park]]\n| Sunday, 23 August\n|-\n| 20\n| Gold Coast\n| 6.14 (50)\n| def by\n| '''[[Geelong Falcons]]'''\n| '''14.7 (91)'''\n| [[Carrara Stadium]]\n| Saturday, 29 August\n|-\n| Elim Final\n| '''Gold Coast'''\n| '''10.17 (77)'''\n| def\n| [[Northern Knights]]\n| 9.9 (63)\n| [[Visy Park]]\n| Saturday, 5 September\n|-\n| Semi Final\n| Gold Coast\n| 5.9 (39)\n| def by\n| '''[[Geelong Falcons]]'''\n| '''11.14 (80)'''\n| [[Visy Park]]\n| Sunday, 13 September\n|}\n|}\n\n===2010: VFL===\nIn November 2009 the team signed twelve 17-year-olds around the country to compete in the [[Victorian Football League]] (VFL) year through the under age access rules. These players included [[Luke Russell]] ([[Burnie Dockers Football Club|Burnie]]), [[Maverick Weller]] ([[Burnie Dockers Football Club|Burnie]]), [[Taylor Hine]] ([[Calder Cannons|Calder]]), [[Josh Toy]] ([[Calder Cannons|Calder]]), [[Matt Shaw]] ([[Dandenong Stingrays|Dandenong]]), [[Piers Flanagan]] ([[Geelong Falcons|Geelong]]), [[Hayden Jolly]] ([[Glenelg Football Club|Glenelg]]), [[Alex Keath]] ([[Murray Bushrangers|Murray]]), [[Jack Hutchins (Australian footballer)|Jack Hutchins]] ([[Sandringham Dragons|Sandringham]]), [[Tom Nicholls]] ([[Sandringham Dragons|Sandringham]]), [[Brandon Matera]] ([[South Fremantle Football Club|South Fremantle]]), [[Trent McKenzie]] ([[Western Jets]]).\n\nThe Gold Coast was also given permission (by the AFL) to play [[David Swallow]] in 2010, despite not being the correct age. The deal that was struck with the AFL stated that Swallow would still need to go through the [[2010 AFL Draft]] to officially join the team, while the other under age recruits contracts would run through 2011.\n\nThese are the results and fixture for the 2010 season, in which the club competed in the [[Victorian Football League]] (VFL).<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.sportingpulse.com/team_info.cgi?c=1-118-81425-102874-11678033&a=SFIX| title = Gold Coast Football Club \u2013 2010 Season Fixture| publisher = VFL.com.au| accessdate = 11 July 2009}}</ref>\n\n===={{anchor|Inaugural VFL team}}Inaugural VFL team====\n{{Aussie rules team | title = Inaugural GCFC team (Round 1, 2010 season)\n| backpocket1 = [[Matt Shaw]]\n| fullback = [[Jack Hutchins (footballer)|Jack Hutchins]]\n| backpocket2 = Michael Gugliotta\n| halfbackflank1 = [[Taylor Hine]]\n| centrehalfback = [[Michael Coad]]\n| halfbackflank2 = [[Maverick Weller]]\n| wing1 = [[Trent McKenzie]]\n| centre = [[Marc Lock]] ([[Captain (Australian rules football)|c]])\n| wing2 = [[Luke Russell]]\n| halfforwardflank1 = [[Alik Magin]]\n| centrehalfforward = [[Charlie Dixon (Australian footballer)|Charlie Dixon]]\n| halfforwardflank2 = [[Brandon Matera]]\n| forwardpocket1 = [[Liam Patrick]]\n| fullforward = [[Nathan Ablett]]\n| forwardpocket2 = [[Rex Liddy]]\n| ruck = [[Zac Smith]]\n| ruckrover = [[Daniel Harris (footballer)|Daniel Harris]]\n| rover = [[Sam Iles]]\n| interchange1 = [[Danny Stanley]]\n| interchange2 = [[Rory Thompson]]\n| interchange3 = [[Hayden Jolly]]\n| interchange4 = [[David Swallow]]\n| interchange5 = Luke Shreeve\n| interchange6 = [[Joseph Daye]]\n| coach = [[Guy McKenna]]\n}}\n\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed wikitable toccolours\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:white; color:black; width:670px;\"|'''Gold Coast Season 2010'''\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| '''Rd'''\n| '''Home team'''\n| '''Score'''\n|\n| '''Away team'''\n| '''Score'''\n| '''Ground'''\n| '''Date'''\n|-\n| 1\n| Gold Coast\n| 15.7 (97)\n| def by\n| '''[[Port Melbourne Football Club|Port Melbourne]]'''\n| 15.19 (109)\n| Fankhauser Reserve\n| Saturday, 10 April\n|-\n| 2\n| Gold Coast\n| 11.11 (77)\n| def by\n| '''[[Williamstown Football Club|Williamstown]]'''\n| 16.17 (113)\n| Merrimac Oval\n| Saturday, 17 April\n|-\n| 3\n| '''[[Werribee Football Club|Werribee]]'''\n| 11.18 (84)\n| drew with\n| '''Gold Coast'''\n| 12.12 (84)\n| [[Chirnside Park]]\n| Saturday, 24 April\n|-\n| 4\n| Gold Coast\n| 10.9 (69)\n| def by\n| '''[[Casey Scorpions]]'''\n| 10.17 (77)\n| Fankhauser Reserve\n| Saturday, 1 May\n|-\n| 5\n| '''[[Bendigo Bombers]]'''\n| 15.17 (107)\n| def\n| Gold Coast\n| 12.9 (81)\n| [[Queen Elizabeth Oval]]\n| Saturday, 8 May\n|-\n| 6\n| '''Gold Coast'''\n| 10.8 (68)\n| def\n| [[Geelong Football Club|Geelong]]\n| 5.10 (40)\n| Fankhauser Reserve\n| Saturday, 15 May\n|-\n| 7\n| Gold Coast\n| 5.8 (38)\n| def by\n| [[Collingwood VFL Football Club|Collingwood]]\n| 7.15 (58)\n| Fankhauser Reserve\n| Saturday, 29 May\n|-\n| 8\n| '''[[Northern Bullants]]'''\n| 26.10 (166)\n| def\n| Gold Coast\n| 9.7 (61)\n| [[Visy Park]]\n| Saturday, 5 June\n|-\n| 9\n| '''[[Coburg Football Club|Coburg Tigers]]'''\n| 17.21 (123)\n| def\n| Gold Coast\n| 11.10 (76)\n| Highgate Recreation Reserve\n| Saturday, 12 June\n|-\n| 10\n| '''Gold Coast'''\n| 15.13 (103)\n| def\n| [[Frankston Football Club|Frankston]]\n| 7.4 (46)\n| Merrimac Oval\n| Saturday, 26 June\n|-\n| 11\n| Gold Coast\n|11.8 (74)\n| def by\n| '''[[Box Hill Hawks Football Club|Box Hill Hawks]]'''\n| 19.16 (130)\n| Fankhauser Reserve\n| Saturday, 3 July\n|-\n| 12\n| '''[[North Ballarat Football Club|North Ballarat]]'''\n| 6.12 (48)\